observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the LCE agreed to require the

(a)General Services Officer to perform the duties and responsibilities outlined under Section 490(b) of the Local Government Code RA 7160;
(b) Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction Management Office (MDRRMO) to furnish the Accounting Office and Committee on Physical Inventory of PPE, a copy of Registry of Donated Relief Goods for DRRM and Acknowledgement Receipts for In-kind Donations for DRRM as bases of recording in the Municipality’s books and reports

(c) Municipal Accountant to

(i) record In-kind Donations received in accordance with Annex Q of COA Circular 2014-002 dated April 15, 2004;



(ii) disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements information pertaining to DRRM particularly the quantity received, issued and balance of donated relief goods as well as the receipt of donated PPE (if any) and its disposal/transfer;

(d) Committee on Physical Inventory of PPE to include the In-kind Donations received in the physical count and its corresponding Inventory Report.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to 

(a) invest on its personnel in the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction Office by providing them the necessary seminar/training pertinent to their function; 

(b) prioritize the procurement of disaster related equipment and;

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive 

(a) create and institutionalize a Solid Waste Management Board and allocate funds specifically for the implementation of SWM plans, programs and activities; 

(b) instruct the designated MENRO to 

(i) review and implement the mandates of RA No. 9003; 

(ii) review the existing 10-year SWM Plan and recommend updates on a yearly basis in accordance with Section 16 of RA No. 9003; 
(iii) recommend to the Sangguniang Bayan (SB) any updates, amendments and ratification of related municipal ordinance, or any policies and measures to make it relevant to the call of the times, as warranted; and 

(c) consider, with appropriate SP action, imposing fines and penalties for violators of the Anti-Littering policy as well as filing of administrative cases against erring government officials as provided by Sections 49 and 50 of RA No. 9003.

We reiterated our previous recommendations that the Local Chief Executive 

(a) instruct the Inventory Committee to (i) conduct a comprehensive and complete physical count of PPE and (ii) submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) to the Office of the Auditor within the prescribed period; 

(b) direct the General Service Office and the Municipal Accountant to complete/update the Property Cards and Property Ledger Cards and perform regular reconciliation thereof.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

instruct the Inventory Committee to conduct a comprehensive physical count of all property of the Municipality including Land Improvements, Public Infrastructures, Buildings and Structures; and Construction-in-Progress and render reports thereon;

require the Municipal Accountant and the acting General Services Officer to reconcile their records for PPE accounts to determine the causes of the variance thereof for proper disposition; 

direct the Municipal Accountant to exert extra effort to locate the necessary records and documents of the PPE accounts amounting to ₱3,857,918.03 to be able to  compute the corresponding depreciation expenses and in order to present the correct carrying value of the said PPE accounts in the financial statements; and

instruct the Municipal Assessor and the acting General Services Officer to register in the name of Municipal Government all the lands which are not yet covered by TCT.

We recommended that the:

Personnel Officer  hire job order personnel  based on necessity for a period not exceeding six months;

Municipal Accountant (i) support disbursements of funds for services rendered by job order personnel with the necessary and appropriate supporting documents to establish validity and propriety of payment; (ii) ensure that daily time records are properly filled-up; and (iii) deductions are made on wages of job order employees with absences.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the acting GSO and the Bids and Awards Committee to procure with PS-DBM all ordinary and common-use supplies and to ensure wide dissemination of procurement opportunities to promote transparency and competitiveness in its procurement and to obtain the price most advantageous to the government.

We also recommended that the BAC undertake procurement proceedings consistent with the RIRR of RA No.  9184, as follows:

adopt public bidding as the appropriate mode of procurement, unless the conditions of the alternative methods of procurement are fully met;

during the planning stage, decide on the mode of procurement so that subsequent adoption of alternative mode shall be subject to the approval of the Head of the Procuring Entity to avoid incidence of splitting of contracts;

post the notice of award to PhilGEPS, the website of the agency, if available, and at any conspicuous place reserved for this purpose in the premises of the agency; and

prepare and submit to GPPB the procurement monitoring report incorporating the required information and in frequency required by regulations

